<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="362" pageId="14" pageNumber="361" type="taxonomic affinities">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="361">Taxonomic affinities.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="362" pageId="14" pageNumber="361">
Belongs to 
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria longicornis" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longicornis">Empria longicornis</taxonomicName>
group. Externally it is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria japonica" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="japonica">Empria japonica</taxonomicName>
, but penis valve is clearly distinct from all other known species of the longicornis-group (Fig. 36), being most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria alpina" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="14" pageNumber="361" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpina">Empria alpina</taxonomicName>
Benson, 1938 (e.g. 
<pageBreakToken pageId="15" pageNumber="362" start="start">http</pageBreakToken>
://www.morphbank.net/?id=577439). Can be distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria alpina" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpina">Empria alpina</taxonomicName>
by its colouration: in 
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Empria</taxonomicName>
sp1 tegulae, posterior margin of pronotum, and basal 1/3 of metatibia are pale, while in 
<taxonomicName authority="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville, 1828" authorityName="Le Peletier &amp; Audinet-Serville" authorityYear="1828" class="Insecta" family="Tenthredinidae" genus="Empria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Empria alpina" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alpina">Empria alpina</taxonomicName>
these are mostly black. Distinctness of this taxon is also supported by nuclear ITS sequence data (Fig. 38).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
